🧩 2946. Matrix Similarity After Cyclic Shifts
📋 Problem Statement

You are given an m x n matrix mat and an integer k.

Operation (performed k times):

Even rows → left cyclic shift
Odd rows → right cyclic shift

👉 Return true if after all operations, the matrix becomes same as original, else false.

🧠 Humanized Intuition (VERY IMPORTANT 🔥)

Instead of actually performing k shifts step by step, think smart:

💡 Key Observation

After n shifts → row becomes same again (cycle complete)

So instead of doing k operations:
👉 Just compute effective shift = k % n

🔄 What does shifting mean?

For a row of length n:

Even row (left shift)
[j] → (j + shift) % n
Odd row (right shift)
[j] → (j - shift + n) % n
🎯 Core Idea

We don’t need to build a new matrix ❌
We just check:

👉 “If I shift virtually, does each element match original?”

If ANY mismatch → return false
Else → return true

🧪 Dry Run
Example:
mat = [[1,2,3],
       [4,5,6],
       [7,8,9]]
k = 4
n = 3 → shift = 4 % 3 = 1

Row 0 → left shift → [2,3,1] ❌ not same
👉 Answer = false

⚡ Optimized Approach
Compute shift = k % n
Traverse each cell (i, j)
Compute where it should come from after shift
Compare with original
💻 Code (Java)
class Solution {
    public boolean areSimilar(int[][] mat, int k) {
        int m = mat.length, n = mat[0].length;
        int shift = k % n;
        
        for (int i = 0; i < m; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j < n; j++) {
                int original = mat[i][j];
                int rotated;
                
                if (i % 2 == 0) { // even row → left shift
                    rotated = mat[i][(j + shift) % n];
                } else { // odd row → right shift
                    rotated = mat[i][(j - shift + n) % n];
                }
                
                if (original != rotated) return false;
            }
        }
        return true;
    }
}
⏱ Complexity Analysis
Type	Complexity
Time	O(m × n)
Space	O(1)